WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.760 --> 00:00:02.010
Google Event
November 19, 2009

00:00:01.900 --> 00:00:02.150
Washington, D.C.

00:00:01.960 --> 00:00:06.319
&gt;&gt;Jonas Klink: All right.
Good morning, everyone.

00:00:06.319 --> 00:00:12.070
My name is Jonas Klink.
And I'm the product manager for the accessibility

00:00:12.070 --> 00:00:16.510
team here at Google.
And we're very, very excited to have you guys

00:00:16.510 --> 00:00:20.170
here today.
I want to extend a really, really warm welcome

00:00:20.170 --> 00:00:24.670
and thank you all for coming here.
I know a lot of you are local.

00:00:24.670 --> 00:00:28.460
But it's still early in the morning.
And we're thrilled to have you here.

00:00:28.460 --> 00:00:32.239
I think we're going to have a great event
today.

00:00:32.239 --> 00:00:37.420
And I look forward to showing you the demo
that we have going today.

00:00:37.420 --> 00:00:43.659
We have an agenda here behind me.
After I do the brief introduction that I'm

00:00:43.659 --> 00:00:47.809
blocking, I'm going to hand it over to Vint
Cerf.

00:00:47.809 --> 00:00:52.100
We're then going to have Ken and Naomi do
some demos.

00:00:52.100 --> 00:00:58.209
Vint will come back to provide a wrap-up.
And then we'll do some Q&amp;A towards the end.

00:00:58.209 --> 00:01:03.249
The bulk of us, the majority, will be available
afterwards to give some additional demos,

00:01:03.249 --> 00:01:06.150
answer more questions, anything you haven't
gotten to.

00:01:06.150 --> 00:01:09.460
So we're really thrilled to have Vint Cerf
with us.

00:01:09.460 --> 00:01:14.120
His title here at Google is vice president
and chief Internet evangelist.

00:01:14.120 --> 00:01:17.340
And -- but as many of you know, he's a lot
more than that.

00:01:17.340 --> 00:01:23.600
He's widely known as the father of the Internet,
as one of the codesigners of the TCP/IP protocol

00:01:23.600 --> 00:01:30.600
and the basic architecture of the Internet.
He, to us, which might be widely known, he's

00:01:31.810 --> 00:01:38.600
really, really critical as an unwavering supporter
for an accessible Internet, and especially

00:01:38.600 --> 00:01:44.100
for those who have special access needs.
So without further ado, we're really thrilled

00:01:44.100 --> 00:01:49.280
to have him here.
And I give you Vint Cerf.

00:01:49.280 --> 00:01:52.840
[ Applause ]
&gt;&gt;Vint Cerf: Thank you, all, very, very much

00:01:52.840 --> 00:01:57.680
for coming.
And welcome to Google's D.C. office.

00:01:57.680 --> 00:02:02.880
It's these kinds of events that have made
us so happy to have this facility here.

00:02:02.880 --> 00:02:08.769
And I hope during the course of 2010, we will
see you back here for other kinds of announcements

00:02:08.769 --> 00:02:14.980
related to our work in accessibility.
Let me start out by -- I'm standing in front

00:02:14.980 --> 00:02:18.829
of these darned slides.
How can we do this so I'm not in the way,

00:02:18.829 --> 00:02:21.499
as I fall off the side?
Okay.

00:02:21.499 --> 00:02:24.939
Can I get the first slide, please.
There we are.

00:02:24.939 --> 00:02:31.189
Everyone should know by this time that Google's
motto is to organize the world's information

00:02:31.189 --> 00:02:37.499
and make it accessible and useful.
And accessible is a really important word

00:02:37.499 --> 00:02:40.019
in the context of what we're going to talk
about today.

00:02:40.019 --> 00:02:47.019
Accessibility comes in a wide range of features.
There are issues for people who are deaf or

00:02:48.499 --> 00:02:55.499
hearing-impaired, or people who have visual
impairments, who have low vision or no vision,

00:02:55.499 --> 00:02:59.189
people who have motor problems, and things
like that.

00:02:59.189 --> 00:03:04.680
Google believes that the world's information
should be accessible to everyone.

00:03:04.680 --> 00:03:09.639
And our interest is in finding ways to achieve
that objective.

00:03:09.639 --> 00:03:14.760
We're far from solving the problem completely.
But today's discussion and announcements will

00:03:14.760 --> 00:03:19.989
show you what I consider to be an important
step in that direction.

00:03:19.989 --> 00:03:22.599
I'm going to cheat and look at my notes.
Hold on.

00:03:22.599 --> 00:03:29.599
And I have to use my damned glasses to do
it.

00:03:29.829 --> 00:03:33.279
I hate to admit that I have to wear these
things.

00:03:33.279 --> 00:03:37.259
Inside of every 66-year-old is a 16-year-old
wondering what happened.

00:03:37.259 --> 00:03:41.950
[ Laughter ]
&gt;&gt;Vint Cerf: So I want to tell you, first

00:03:41.950 --> 00:03:46.609
of all, why accessibility's personally important
to me.

00:03:46.609 --> 00:03:50.459
Sigrid, who is in the audience over there
 -- wave your hand, Sigrid -- and I are both

00:03:50.459 --> 00:03:54.489
hearing-impaired.
Sigrid was totally deaf for 50 years.

00:03:54.489 --> 00:03:58.469
She now has two cochlear implants.
And they work wonderfully well.

00:03:58.469 --> 00:04:02.129
They work so well, we had to buy a bigger
house, because she wanted bigger parties,

00:04:02.129 --> 00:04:07.029
because she could hear.
So this is a technology which is spectacular.

00:04:07.029 --> 00:04:09.680
I've been wearing hearing aids since I was
13.

00:04:09.680 --> 00:04:12.099
You can do the math.
That's 53 years.

00:04:12.099 --> 00:04:18.250
So both of us care a great deal about how
technology can help people with various impairments

00:04:18.250 --> 00:04:22.160
get access to information and be connected
with the rest of the world.

00:04:22.160 --> 00:04:27.810
So quite apart from my job at Google, I have
great personal interest in what we're talking

00:04:27.810 --> 00:04:34.810
about today.
You know, YouTube is another part of the Google

00:04:34.900 --> 00:04:37.720
family.
And you saw the signs, I hope, that said Google

00:04:37.720 --> 00:04:43.920
and YouTube are hosting this meeting.
YouTube uncovered an extraordinary desire

00:04:43.920 --> 00:04:50.570
by the world's population to express itself
using the video medium.

00:04:50.570 --> 00:04:55.630
And one of the big challenges of the video
medium is whether it can be made accessible

00:04:55.630 --> 00:04:59.480
to everyone.
It's a little hard to make video accessible

00:04:59.480 --> 00:05:03.270
to people who are blind.
You need to have some kind of descriptive

00:05:03.270 --> 00:05:08.140
ability there.
But for people who are deaf, that's another

00:05:08.140 --> 00:05:13.540
important area of concern, because they may
not be able to hear people speaking.

00:05:13.540 --> 00:05:19.890
So video has turned out to be a stunningly
important new medium for personal expression.

00:05:19.890 --> 00:05:26.890
You may not know the statistics, but there
are 23 hours of video uploaded into YouTube

00:05:26.970 --> 00:05:31.660
every minute.
23 hours of video per minute.

00:05:31.660 --> 00:05:36.730
Now, I have no idea how many hours of video
are actually being watched, but I think the

00:05:36.730 --> 00:05:43.730
answer is bigger than that, although, for
some videos, it may be like blogs, the average

00:05:43.910 --> 00:05:50.910
number of readers of a blog is probably 1.1,
the person that wrote the blog and his dog.

00:05:51.070 --> 00:05:57.230
But these videos are often extremely popular.
And if you haven't noticed, they have become

00:05:57.230 --> 00:06:04.230
an important medium of political expression.
You saw this very evidently in the post-Iran

00:06:05.390 --> 00:06:11.220
elections, where many people used video and
YouTube, in particular, to tell the rest of

00:06:11.220 --> 00:06:18.220
the world what was going on in that country.
Well, we started our life at Google as a company

00:06:19.010 --> 00:06:23.850
that was indexing the Internet.
We crawled through all the billions of pages

00:06:23.850 --> 00:06:29.780
on the net and we try to index them and then
help people find the information that they're

00:06:29.780 --> 00:06:35.090
interested in.
We'd like to extend that ability to find information

00:06:35.090 --> 00:06:40.600
to other media besides text.
And so part of what we are about at Google

00:06:40.600 --> 00:06:46.170
is finding other ways of indexing content
that may not necessarily be purely textual

00:06:46.170 --> 00:06:50.510
in nature.
We move very, very quickly when it comes to

00:06:50.510 --> 00:06:53.780
new ideas.
And we usually get them out there early.

00:06:53.780 --> 00:06:57.350
So beta testing is a very common thing for
us.

00:06:57.350 --> 00:07:02.240
We put new products out there and find out
what people do with them.

00:07:02.240 --> 00:07:08.460
An example of this is Google Wave, where we
put that out very, very early in its development.

00:07:08.460 --> 00:07:14.490
And we're discovering very interesting things
about how people use this combined communication

00:07:14.490 --> 00:07:21.490
tool, which incorporates blogging, instant
messaging, e-mail, and many other forms of

00:07:21.660 --> 00:07:25.670
interaction.
We're very interested in picking up other

00:07:25.670 --> 00:07:30.390
kinds of content than text.
So you see this with Google Earth.

00:07:30.390 --> 00:07:35.110
You see it with Google Maps.
And you see it with attempts to allow people

00:07:35.110 --> 00:07:41.680
to express information or display information
that's geographically indexed by using our

00:07:41.680 --> 00:07:48.680
Google Earth and Google Maps facilities.
We're looking for all kinds of ways of improving

00:07:48.740 --> 00:07:54.000
people's ability to find information.
So some of you may be using the Google Toolbar,

00:07:54.000 --> 00:08:01.000
which we put -- or make available so that
you can easily invoke a Google search.

00:08:01.270 --> 00:08:08.270
We're also very interested in internationalization.
We've recently announced that we are capable

00:08:08.300 --> 00:08:13.330
of searching and translating 51 different
languages.

00:08:13.330 --> 00:08:18.030
Now, there are some linguists in the crowd.
I'm going to pick on my good friend Marc Okrand,

00:08:18.030 --> 00:08:22.389
who is a wonderful linguist at the National
Captioning Institute.

00:08:22.389 --> 00:08:27.680
I know you have heard this, but I have to
tell everybody, Marc is the inventor of the

00:08:27.680 --> 00:08:32.560
Klingon language.
He's a linguist.

00:08:32.560 --> 00:08:37.719
And I'm sure he can appreciate the translating
51 languages into 51 other languages, which

00:08:37.719 --> 00:08:43.360
is a nontrivial exercise.
I also have to admit that we don't do equally

00:08:43.360 --> 00:08:49.870
well with all language pairs.
I tried Chinese to Danish while I was in Copenhagen

00:08:49.870 --> 00:08:52.810
earlier this week.
And since I don't speak either language, I

00:08:52.810 --> 00:08:56.840
don't know how well or poorly I did.
But I noticed there were some chuck unless

00:08:56.840 --> 00:09:02.700
the Danish-speaking audience.
But the point here is that we recognize accessibility

00:09:02.700 --> 00:09:09.700
as being another -- accessibility by way of
language as being another important kind of

00:09:09.800 --> 00:09:10.370
accessibility.
So I want to get the first slide up -- or

00:09:10.370 --> 00:09:10.620
next slide up, if I could.
It's up there now.

00:09:10.370 --> 00:09:13.430
Okay.
So what we're seeing here are some statistics

00:09:13.430 --> 00:09:18.890
basically, relative statistics of the number
of people who speak various languages who

00:09:18.890 --> 00:09:24.080
are on the Internet.
But you'll notice that the blue-colored bars

00:09:24.080 --> 00:09:30.420
illustrate people who have accessibility challenges.
So there are more people with problems of

00:09:30.420 --> 00:09:35.640
color vision than there are Japanese or Spanish
or German or French or of the other language

00:09:35.640 --> 00:09:40.200
speakers.
Or people with poor vision exceed and represent

00:09:40.200 --> 00:09:45.550
a significant part of the Internet user population,
or people with poor dexterity, or people who

00:09:45.550 --> 00:09:51.360
are deaf or hard of hearing and blind.
So what we're saying here with these data

00:09:51.360 --> 00:09:57.270
is that there are a significant number of
people in the Internet population who will

00:09:57.270 --> 00:10:03.270
benefit from improvements in accessibility.
And we recognize this on a global scale.

00:10:03.270 --> 00:10:09.930
We try to serve users, all 1.7 billion of
them who are online on the Internet today.

00:10:09.930 --> 00:10:16.930
And we would like to improve the ability of
our users who have disabilities to get access

00:10:17.740 --> 00:10:24.740
to the information that we can provide.
So let me just give you a couple of examples

00:10:25.740 --> 00:10:30.010
of the things that we do.
In Google Applications or Google Apps, we've

00:10:30.010 --> 00:10:37.010
been focusing on keyboard access and the use
assistive technologies like screen-readers

00:10:37.880 --> 00:10:43.710
to make the information available more accessible
to people who can't see.

00:10:43.710 --> 00:10:47.760
We've released android operating system for
mobiles.

00:10:47.760 --> 00:10:51.610
And our intent was to keep that as open as
possible.

00:10:51.610 --> 00:10:56.770
It's an open source operating system.
People can add functionality to it.

00:10:56.770 --> 00:11:02.400
And one of the things we would like to facilitate
is the addition of assistive methods to make

00:11:02.400 --> 00:11:08.890
the operating system more useful in a mobile
context for people who need help.

00:11:08.890 --> 00:11:15.220
We also released a browser called Chrome.
And in addition to its security properties,

00:11:15.220 --> 00:11:21.620
which we believe are superior, it is also
an open platform, one in which assistive mechanisms

00:11:21.620 --> 00:11:28.000
can be incorporated.
And, finally, YouTube itself, in 2006, added

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:35.000
the ability to put captions up on the YouTube
videos if the supplier of that video had captioning

00:11:37.810 --> 00:11:41.560
transcripts available and could insert them
into the video.

00:11:41.560 --> 00:11:47.930
So we're very interested in helping people
with that kind of information to make it easily

00:11:47.930 --> 00:11:53.060
accessible to the rest of the world.
So I'm going to stop here and just remind

00:11:53.060 --> 00:12:00.060
you again that Google is fully prepared to
pursue accessibility features in all of our

00:12:00.960 --> 00:12:07.220
products and services, and we're here to tell
you about some specific ones today.

00:12:07.220 --> 00:12:11.700
And to do that, I want to introduce my good
friend Ken Harrenstien.

00:12:11.700 --> 00:12:14.870
Ken and I have known each other for probably
over 30 years.

00:12:14.870 --> 00:12:18.460
I think we were two or three years old at
the time when we met.

00:12:18.460 --> 00:12:24.089
Ken was at SRI International on the West Coast.
He and I worked on something called Deaf Net,

00:12:24.089 --> 00:12:31.089
which was an extremely early attempt to bring
terminal access to the Internet to people

00:12:31.510 --> 00:12:37.670
who were using TTYs and things of that kind.
I would say we had mixed results with that

00:12:37.670 --> 00:12:42.330
experiment.
But we learned a lot from how much value there

00:12:42.330 --> 00:12:46.220
came from having access to the Internet through
these tools.

00:12:46.220 --> 00:12:53.220
But in the meantime, Ken has joined Google.
And of all the people that I know at Google,

00:12:57.180 --> 00:13:02.730
Ken has been the strongest proponent and one
of the strongest technical contributors to

00:13:02.730 --> 00:13:07.740
our accessibility initiatives.
He's very, very vocal and passionate on the

00:13:07.740 --> 00:13:10.970
subject.
And he's going to show you what he and his

00:13:10.970 --> 00:13:16.420
colleagues have been able to do in this area.
So, Ken, thank you so much for coming here

00:13:16.420 --> 00:13:23.400
to the East Coast.
Let me turn the microphone over to you.

00:13:23.400 --> 00:13:30.400
[ Applause ]
&gt;&gt;Ken Harrenstien: Thank you, Vint.

00:13:31.070 --> 00:13:36.960
Hi, everyone.
My name is Ken Harrenstien.

00:13:36.960 --> 00:13:40.640
As you can see, I'm a software engineer, and
I work for Google.

00:13:40.640 --> 00:13:47.640
It's always such a great honor to share the
stage here with Vint.

00:13:49.959 --> 00:13:56.800
But for me personally, it's even a bigger
honor to have all of you here, because I know

00:13:56.800 --> 00:14:03.800
for all of us, we've worked many, many years
diligently pursuing the same goal.

00:14:04.190 --> 00:14:08.850
We share the same frustrations.
And today I'm really happen to be able to

00:14:08.850 --> 00:14:15.060
share something that we hope that will reach
this goal of accessibility, something we've

00:14:15.060 --> 00:14:22.060
worked on hard.
Since some of you probably don't know a lot

00:14:27.420 --> 00:14:34.420
about YouTube and the captioning services
that we can do, I'd like to start by reviewing

00:14:34.420 --> 00:14:38.800
quickly some of what we already provide.
And then we'll talk about the problems that

00:14:38.800 --> 00:14:42.800
we're facing.
And lastly, we'll talk about how we're trying

00:14:42.800 --> 00:14:49.800
to solve those problems.
First, I'll start with a little demonstration.

00:14:53.300 --> 00:14:57.870
This video is one we made when we first launched
captions on YouTube.

00:14:57.870 --> 00:15:04.870
It was really fun making it.
So let me play some.

00:15:05.410 --> 00:15:12.410
As you can see, I'm changing the size.
People want to see sometimes more video than

00:15:22.420 --> 00:15:25.050
they want to see captions.
But if you're in the back, you may want to

00:15:25.050 --> 00:15:32.050
see them a little bit bigger.
Is that better?

00:15:33.350 --> 00:15:40.350
I'll explain the details later how to do it.
Also, for some people who want to see more

00:15:45.790 --> 00:15:52.790
of the video, you can turn off the background.
That's an option.

00:15:53.339 --> 00:15:57.029
Most people like the black background, as
it makes it easier to read.

00:15:57.029 --> 00:16:03.200
So I'll leave it on that way.
Can you read this all right?

00:16:03.200 --> 00:16:10.200
Is that

00:16:48.890 --> 00:16:55.890
all right for everyone?
I should look in the back there.

00:16:57.930 --> 00:17:02.680
Okay.
Let me play a little bit.

00:17:02.680 --> 00:17:04.720
(Video).
(No audio).

00:17:04.720 --> 00:17:06.760
[ Laughter ]
(Speaking French).

00:17:06.760 --> 00:17:10.829
&gt;&gt;Ken Harrenstien: He's speaking French.
(Video.)

00:17:10.829 --> 00:17:17.829
&gt;&gt;Ken Harrenstien: Now, Japanese is being
spoken.

00:17:20.959 --> 00:17:25.760
This person here, his name is HIROTO.
He's our product manager.

00:17:25.760 --> 00:17:29.640
He's done a great job.
Unfortunately, he couldn't come here today.

00:17:29.640 --> 00:17:36.640
But he's here on video.
So what I just demonstrated is how captions

00:17:38.780 --> 00:17:44.740
have made videos accessible to everyone.
It doesn't matter if you can hear or not.

00:17:44.740 --> 00:17:50.160
You know, for people who don't understand
Japanese, if you don't understand sign language,

00:17:50.160 --> 00:17:56.530
it's all made accessible through captions.
Now, suppose English isn't your first language.

00:17:56.530 --> 00:18:02.740
This has several captions that are already
uploaded.

00:18:02.740 --> 00:18:09.740
So I'm able to pick another language.
I'll pick this one.

00:18:16.620 --> 00:18:23.620
And does anyone speak this?
(Non-English language).

00:18:29.220 --> 00:18:36.220
&gt;&gt;Ken Harrenstien: Now, suppose in that list
of prepared captions you don't see the language

00:18:40.320 --> 00:18:47.320
that you want.
As Vint mentioned already, we support 51 languages.

00:18:47.570 --> 00:18:52.390
So it's possible to translate to any one of
those other languages.

00:18:52.390 --> 00:18:59.390
Some are better than the others.
But let me show you.

00:19:04.480 --> 00:19:07.250
See this one?
It says "translate captions."

00:19:07.250 --> 00:19:14.250
So I'll pick that.
Now it's translating from English to -- let's

00:19:15.750 --> 00:19:19.970
pick one.
Normally, I like to ask people to help me

00:19:19.970 --> 00:19:22.600
pick.
But I know there's a few people who do speak

00:19:22.600 --> 00:19:29.600
French.
So I'm going to go ahead and choose that.

00:19:33.790 --> 00:19:40.790
&gt;&gt;Video: (Captions French).
&gt;&gt;Ken Harrenstien: What do you think?

00:19:50.540 --> 00:19:57.540
Is it okay?
He still is speaking Japanese, but we can

00:20:01.260 --> 00:20:08.260
read it in French.
Those things are wonderful for accessibility.

00:20:15.500 --> 00:20:19.860
But there's another very cool benefit of having
captions.

00:20:19.860 --> 00:20:26.860
Because they are text, we can search on them.
There's two things that we can do with that.

00:20:28.040 --> 00:20:32.380
It helps you find the video you're looking
for.

00:20:32.380 --> 00:20:37.470
And, secondly, it helps you find the exact
text you want within the video.

00:20:37.470 --> 00:20:40.120
Let me show you that.
It's called a snippet.

00:20:40.120 --> 00:20:43.970
And you can jump directly to the snippet within
the video that you're searching for.

00:20:43.970 --> 00:20:50.970
So let me demonstrate that next.
Here, we see the page from Google.

00:20:54.020 --> 00:21:00.390
It's an advanced video search page.
I've already put in the phrase that I want

00:21:00.390 --> 00:21:03.480
to search for.
"That's one small step."

00:21:03.480 --> 00:21:10.480
This is one of my favorites.
I've also checked this box "Search only closed-captioned

00:21:11.950 --> 00:21:17.410
videos."
So we check that box.

00:21:17.410 --> 00:21:24.410
So here we go.
I found several.

00:21:27.480 --> 00:21:34.480
It happens to know what I want.
Now, you'll notice, it found snippets.

00:21:45.200 --> 00:21:52.200
And you'll know that by offering this option,
start playing at search term.

00:21:52.250 --> 00:21:55.460
So I'll click that.
And it will jump me right there.

00:21:55.460 --> 00:22:01.570
Well, actually, it jumps to a place just a
little bit before, because it knows that you

