00:50:46.230 --> 00:50:53.230
in today's video world.
You are aware, I'm sure, of the late '70s,

00:50:53.230 --> 00:50:58.920
when we had line 21 captioning, and we fought
very hard, some of us, to put that in, even

00:50:58.920 --> 00:51:02.440
though there were people saying, well, there
were better ways to do it and we should wait

00:51:02.440 --> 00:51:08.190
until video text was available, because it
would have a wider variety of symbols that

00:51:08.190 --> 00:51:10.720
could be expressed.
And most of us said, the heck with that.

00:51:10.720 --> 00:51:16.020
Just get something up so we can appreciate
video like everyone else does.

00:51:16.020 --> 00:51:21.700
Then, of course, we've come to high-definition
television.

00:51:21.700 --> 00:51:26.579
By the way, I should tell you that YouTube
has just announced that it can put up 1080P,

00:51:26.579 --> 00:51:32.339
the highest resolution, highest definition
that you can watch on YouTube.

00:51:32.339 --> 00:51:34.460
So we're moving ahead with the rest of the
industry.

00:51:34.460 --> 00:51:41.250
But some of you probably know that high-definition
captioning hasn't worked terribly well.

00:51:41.250 --> 00:51:47.160
It's, I would say, erratic.
The Federal Communications Commission has

00:51:47.160 --> 00:51:53.329
a whole group assigned to work on that problem.
And I can tell you that on behalf of Google,

00:51:53.329 --> 00:51:56.359
I'm going to be digging as deep into that
as I can.

00:51:56.359 --> 00:52:00.710
But what's very interesting about what you're
seeing here is that the captions are being

00:52:00.710 --> 00:52:05.109
delivered differently than they are with traditional
television.

00:52:05.109 --> 00:52:11.329
They are distinct and separate channels, so
to speak, not in the sense that Naomi was

00:52:11.329 --> 00:52:17.710
talking about, but in the sense of the source
of the captions is independent of the video.

00:52:17.710 --> 00:52:20.450
They're obviously linked together by the time
codes.

00:52:20.450 --> 00:52:27.310
But because they are segregated, we can do
all these things to manipulate the text file.

00:52:27.310 --> 00:52:32.839
We can translate from one language to another.
We can automatically do the partitioning.

00:52:32.839 --> 00:52:36.339
We can give you the transcript so you can
do editing on it.

00:52:36.339 --> 00:52:43.170
You don't have to have all the kinds of equipment
that are needed to decode the captions or

00:52:43.170 --> 00:52:46.349
to encode the captions.
It's a separate process.

00:52:46.349 --> 00:52:53.160
This separation of the two media, the text
medium and the video medium, creates opportunities

00:52:53.160 --> 00:52:59.260
that would not otherwise exist.
And so when you think about things like I.P.

00:52:59.260 --> 00:53:06.260
TV, you should not be thinking of just generating
and distributing a kind of condensed combined

00:53:10.530 --> 00:53:16.970
medium, but, rather, one in which the separation
is important because of the ability to manipulate

00:53:16.970 --> 00:53:19.339
it.
And so if we're looking towards the future

00:53:19.339 --> 00:53:25.160
of this medium, the ability to separately
manage these different streams is absolutely

00:53:25.160 --> 00:53:28.940
critical.
Oddly enough, there is something kind of like

00:53:28.940 --> 00:53:33.150
